   "source": [
    "# A Rule-Based Database Grounding Framework for Evaluating LLM-Generated Travel Itineraries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0965ea76-aa1e-4b6e-bbfd-1027b420d2bb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "With the rapid integration of Large Language Models (LLMs) into personalized travel planning, automated itinerary generation has become a highly sought-after application. However, LLMs frequently suffer from hallucinations and weak spatiotemporal reasoning. They often propose itineraries that ignore real-world constraints such as physical distance, transit times, and specific business operating schedules or weekly closing days.\n",
    "\n",
    "This project addresses these limitations by developing a lightweight, automated evaluation framework. By coupling a relational Ground Truth Database with a Python-powered Rule Engine, we systematically validate and score the physical consistency of travel itineraries generated by LLMs."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d3450a2e-5612-4101-95aa-5beff864b906",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Evaluation Process\n",
    "\n",
    "* **Data preparation:** Build a taxonomy and ontology in SQLite.\n",
    "* **Inference:** Collect LLM-generated itineraries and convert them into structured data.\n",
    "* **Validation:** Validate each itinerary against the grounding database and rule set.\n",
    "* **Scoring:** Calculate quality metrics and summarize evaluation results.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e11391ea-22d1-4edc-b38e-427a25a2b9cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Project Steps\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Create a persistent grounding database containing locations, relationships, and constraints.\n",
    "2. Prepare representative LLM-generated itinerary responses.\n",
    "3. Evaluate itinerary quality using rule-based checks.\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "51ea24ac-38f6-4d5c-8605-06edee2d4f13",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# System Architecture and Database Design\n",
    "\n",
    "The system uses a persistent, file-based SQLite database (`travel_grounding.db`) so that reference data can be queried and reused across evaluation runs. The schema contains three relational tables:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **`locations` — entity registry and taxonomy**\n",
    "   * `id`, `name`, `type`, `district`, `required_time`\n",
    "   * `required_time` represents the recommended visit duration in hours.\n",
    "\n",
    "2. **`relation_data` — spatial ontology**\n",
    "   * `origin_id`, `destination_id`, `distance_km`, `transit_min`\n",
    "   * Stores distance and estimated public-transit time between pairs of locations.\n",
    "\n",
    "3. **`constraints` — operating rules**\n",
    "   * `location_id`, `closed_day`, `open_time`, `close_time`, `require_reservation`\n",
    "   * `closed_day` uses `0–6` for Monday–Sunday and `7` for open every day.\n",
    "   * `require_reservation` is stored as a Boolean integer: `1` for required and `0` for not required.\n"
   ]
  },
